The paper deals with approximation algorithms for Steiner forest and its generalizations in the Euclidean plane, which are classic problems in computational geometry and graph theory. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely category. The paper also introduces a new structural property and modifies dynamic programming, which are techniques commonly used in cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also discusses the multiplicative case of prize-collecting and budgeted Steiner forest, which involves optimization and approximation, and thus may fall under cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Finally, the paper discusses the hardness of PTASs for these problems in the general Euclidean case, which is a topic in cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
